WEBVTT

00:02.711 --> 00:03.545
[bright tone]

00:05.380 --> 00:07.048
- Hey, do you have a sec?
- Mm-hmm.

00:07.048 --> 00:08.508
Uh, so we were talking
about something

00:08.508 --> 00:10.051
in my management class
last night.

00:10.051 --> 00:11.511
Did you guys know we're behind

00:11.511 --> 00:13.013
most of the other
auto companies in green tech?

00:13.013 --> 00:16.391
We got a slow start on EVs,
thanks to a previous CEO.

00:16.391 --> 00:17.726
Yeah,
my grandfather always said,

00:17.726 --> 00:20.186
"Electric cars are
for European sissies."

00:20.186 --> 00:21.688
And I know that sounds bad,

00:21.688 --> 00:23.356
but he didn't mean people
from Europe.

00:23.356 --> 00:24.524
He meant effeminate men.

00:24.524 --> 00:25.984
I'm pretty sure that's worse.

00:25.984 --> 00:28.570
Well, this analyst was
talking to our class about it,

00:28.570 --> 00:30.905
and she says that every time
a auto company announces

00:30.905 --> 00:33.867
a green initiative,
the stock price shoots up.

00:33.867 --> 00:35.076
- Well...
- Yeah.

00:35.076 --> 00:37.203
We do need
to boost our stock price.

00:37.203 --> 00:39.205
Have I told you about
the sacrifice that I made

00:39.205 --> 00:40.707
- to save your jobs?
- You did.

00:40.707 --> 00:42.000
Oh, no, I just didn't know
if you were there

00:42.000 --> 00:44.002
- when I told everyone, so--
- We were all there.

00:44.002 --> 00:45.628
It was pretty selfless,
so okay.

00:45.628 --> 00:47.547
Well, yeah.
Let's announce it.

00:47.547 --> 00:49.382
What exactly am I announcing?

00:49.382 --> 00:52.218
Say we're investing 2 billion
into EV

00:52.218 --> 00:54.721
with plans
to go completely green by,

00:54.721 --> 00:55.764
I don't know, 2040?

00:55.764 --> 00:57.098
And are we actually
going green

00:57.098 --> 00:58.516
or just announcing it?

00:58.516 --> 01:00.393
Um, both.
We'll put the press release out

01:00.393 --> 01:02.771
now for the stock bump,
and you take all the time

01:02.771 --> 01:04.606
that you need
designing your solar wheels

01:04.606 --> 01:06.983
or an engine that runs
on hot-dog water

01:06.983 --> 01:08.234
or whatever gets you hard.

01:08.234 --> 01:10.403
- Everyone's happy.
- Does $2 billion--

01:10.403 --> 01:12.072
does that sound a little fake, though,

01:12.072 --> 01:14.074
like Dr. Evil or something?

01:14.074 --> 01:15.825
- Do not.
- Well, you could say

01:15.825 --> 01:17.535
like $1.7 billion.

01:17.535 --> 01:18.870
Oh, yeah. No, that's good.

01:18.870 --> 01:20.330
It'll look like we tried
to reach 2 billion

01:20.330 --> 01:21.331
- but couldn't.
- [sighs]

01:21.331 --> 01:23.124
Oh, my God, fine. Do it.

01:23.124 --> 01:25.585
[as Dr. Evil]
$2 million.

01:25.585 --> 01:28.797
- Billion.
- $2 billion.

01:30.173 --> 01:31.841
Zip it.

01:31.841 --> 01:33.885
<i>* Bom bom
bom-bom-bom-bom-bom ♪</i>

01:33.885 --> 01:36.096
<i>♪ Buh buh bom-bom-bom
buh bom-bom-bom-bom ♪</i>

01:36.096 --> 01:39.015
<i>[chorus vocalizing]</i>

01:39.015 --> 01:40.141
Did you see this?

01:40.141 --> 01:41.559
Our stock's already up
four points.

01:41.559 --> 01:43.103
- It totally worked.
- I saw.

01:43.103 --> 01:44.270
We should do
a second announcement

01:44.270 --> 01:45.522
and see if the price
goes up even more.

01:45.522 --> 01:46.690
I'm not sure
that's a good idea.

01:46.690 --> 01:48.149
The stock price is up
four points.

01:48.149 --> 01:49.275
- I saw.
- Let's do a second

01:49.275 --> 01:50.318
announcement.
It'll boost the price

01:50.318 --> 01:51.695
- even more.
- I said the same thing.

01:51.695 --> 01:53.446
How do we justify
a second press release

01:53.446 --> 01:55.615
on the same day
about the same thing?

01:55.615 --> 01:58.159
Uh, it's green stuff
so, uh, climate change?

01:58.159 --> 01:59.577
Oh, yeah. That's perfect.

01:59.577 --> 02:00.912
- Hmm.
- "As the situation

02:00.912 --> 02:02.288
"with climate change evolves,

02:02.288 --> 02:03.915
so must our plans," et cetera.

02:03.915 --> 02:05.709
Uh, make sure that you use
the word "unprecedented."

02:05.709 --> 02:06.835
- Ooh, that's nice.
- Sure.

02:06.835 --> 02:09.671
And say we're investing
3.27 billion.

02:09.671 --> 02:11.006
- Oh.
- And we'll be green

02:11.006 --> 02:12.590
- by the year--
- Uh, 2030.

02:12.590 --> 02:14.342
- Love it.
- Okay, anything earlier

02:14.342 --> 02:16.302
than 2035 is gonna sound crazy.

02:16.302 --> 02:18.555
Can we at least say 2034?

02:18.555 --> 02:21.141
- Okay, 2034.
- 2033?

02:21.141 --> 02:23.101
Fine, 2034.

02:23.101 --> 02:25.270
Sounds like you're learning
a lot in that program.

02:25.270 --> 02:27.897
You know, I was never
into academics as a kid,

02:27.897 --> 02:30.692
but this stuff is--
is actually really interesting.

02:30.692 --> 02:32.819
Well, I'm very happy for you.

02:32.819 --> 02:36.322
Like in my last class, there
was an example of a company,

02:36.322 --> 02:37.866
- Merlin Enterprises.
- Uh-huh.

02:37.866 --> 02:39.284
And Merlin makes widgets.

02:39.284 --> 02:40.660
But one day they decided

02:40.660 --> 02:42.704
that they also wanna make
scrunchems, right?

02:42.704 --> 02:44.080
Right, yeah.
Well, I gotta go--

02:44.080 --> 02:45.206
It's all made-up.

02:45.206 --> 02:46.708
There is no Merlin Enterprises.

02:46.708 --> 02:48.668
But for the sake
of the example, I--

02:48.668 --> 02:49.961
John! [exhales]

02:49.961 --> 02:51.755
[softly] Sorry, I gotta go deal
with this.

02:51.755 --> 02:53.465
[laughs] John!

02:53.465 --> 02:56.217
We gotta go over some stuff.

02:57.886 --> 03:00.263
He really wanted
to get away from you.

03:00.263 --> 03:01.681
Thank you, Dale.

03:01.681 --> 03:03.183
You click Refresh.
You've got the magic touch.

03:03.183 --> 03:04.559
Okay.

03:04.559 --> 03:06.519
- Oh! Up six cents.
- Whoa, hey, hey! Yes.

03:06.519 --> 03:07.687
We're up another point
and a half.

03:07.687 --> 03:09.314
Hey, we gotta do
a third announcement.

03:09.314 --> 03:11.191
We have to.
The stock market is obsessed

03:11.191 --> 03:12.567
with us right now,
like so horny.

03:12.567 --> 03:13.985
Right, um, I just got a call

03:13.985 --> 03:15.320
from "The Wall Street Journal."

03:15.320 --> 03:16.696
Good news is, they think

03:16.696 --> 03:18.406
that everything we're saying
is super exciting.

03:18.406 --> 03:19.908
Uh, no doy,
"Wall Street Journal."

03:19.908 --> 03:21.201
I was just about to say that.
I was just about to say

03:21.201 --> 03:22.994
- "No doy."
- But they're also curious

03:22.994 --> 03:26.247
to know specifically
what we're doing in terms of,

03:26.247 --> 03:28.041
- you know, going green.
- Already?

03:28.041 --> 03:29.751
We just announced this thing.

03:29.751 --> 03:31.753
Well, if we don't give them
any specifics,

03:31.753 --> 03:33.129
it'll seem like we're all talk,

03:33.129 --> 03:35.048
and our stock price'll go
back down to where it was,

03:35.048 --> 03:36.925
probably lower, actually.

03:38.927 --> 03:41.221
Cyrus! Get in here!

03:41.221 --> 03:43.264
You know, they wouldn't be
doing this if I was a man.

03:43.264 --> 03:44.974
- Holding you accountable?
- Mm-hmm.

03:44.974 --> 03:46.601
You know my office has
a phone, right?

03:46.601 --> 03:47.811
We need to give
"The Wall Street Journal"

03:47.811 --> 03:49.604
some specifics
on the new green initiative.

03:49.604 --> 03:51.564
- What do you got so far?
- The initiative you asked me

03:51.564 --> 03:53.692
to start thinking about
roughly three hours ago?

03:53.692 --> 03:54.984
- Not a whole lot.
- What have you been doing

03:54.984 --> 03:56.194
- this whole time?
- Sorry.

03:56.194 --> 03:57.404
It might take me a whole week

03:57.404 --> 03:59.489
to solve
the global energy crisis.

03:59.489 --> 04:01.241
What if we invest
in some green tech,

04:01.241 --> 04:02.909
like the other companies
we're developing?

04:02.909 --> 04:04.285
Yeah,
that'd show "Wall Street"

04:04.285 --> 04:05.912
that we're serious at least.

04:05.912 --> 04:08.206
We have
an untapped acquisition fund.

04:08.206 --> 04:09.332
- Mm.
- And I know about some

04:09.332 --> 04:10.834
promising start-ups
in Silicon Valley.

04:10.834 --> 04:13.253
- Great. Make us a list.
- Okay.

04:13.253 --> 04:15.755
Looks like
we're going shopping!

04:15.755 --> 04:18.383
Cha-ching,
a little retail therapy.

04:18.383 --> 04:19.843
[laughs] Mama likes
to swipe that plastic.

04:19.843 --> 04:21.428
- Mm.
- Just give Mama the cash

04:21.428 --> 04:22.721
and Mama will spend it.

04:22.721 --> 04:24.139
[as a baby]
Mama buy something for baby?

04:24.139 --> 04:25.849
Toy for baby?

04:27.767 --> 04:30.186
Um, let's maybe all just sit
quietly in our offices

04:30.186 --> 04:31.312
for the rest of the day.

04:36.109 --> 04:37.318
This feels good, guys.
We're literally on our way

04:37.986 --> 04:39.154
to help save the planet.

04:39.154 --> 04:40.697
He said while flying
on a private plane,

04:40.697 --> 04:42.490
drinking
from single-use plastic.

04:42.490 --> 04:44.492
So we have meetings set up
with nine start-ups

04:44.492 --> 04:47.328
that are all working
on EV-related technology.

04:47.328 --> 04:48.496
First there's Loband--

04:48.496 --> 04:49.664
I don't need all the details.

04:49.664 --> 04:51.041
This is lottery
ticket investing.

04:51.041 --> 04:52.375
You buy ten.
You hope you get a winner.

04:52.375 --> 04:54.252
Perfect.
Great business model.

04:54.252 --> 04:55.378
We should meet
with my buddy Chase.

04:55.378 --> 04:56.713
He's a huge tech guy.

04:56.713 --> 04:58.214
Oh, I--I doubt
we'll have time.

04:58.214 --> 04:59.632
No, seriously.
He's a disruptor.

04:59.632 --> 05:03.511
Like imagine a version of me,
but in Silicon Valley.

05:03.511 --> 05:04.888
Hmm.

05:04.888 --> 05:06.389
Um, I should probably get
into these.

05:06.389 --> 05:08.266
<i>Everyone, please be
seated for landing.</i>

05:08.266 --> 05:09.934
Well, I hope you all brought
your umbrellas,

05:09.934 --> 05:12.645
'cause we're about
to make it rain on some nerds.

05:12.645 --> 05:14.564
<i>* It's coming up,
it's coming up ♪</i>

05:14.564 --> 05:16.066
<i>♪ It's dare, uh ♪</i>

05:16.066 --> 05:17.776
We anticipate
that our solar cells

05:17.776 --> 05:20.111
will be able to charge up
to 200% faster

05:20.111 --> 05:21.988
than conventional solar arrays.

05:21.988 --> 05:24.741
So-lar, so good. [laughs]
It's exciting.

05:24.741 --> 05:26.368
How 'bout, uh, 5 million
for 5%?

05:26.368 --> 05:27.786
I know what you're thinking:
this looks like

05:27.786 --> 05:29.496
an ordinary
electrical resolver.

05:29.496 --> 05:31.289
This one is coil-free.

05:31.289 --> 05:32.999
[gasps]

05:32.999 --> 05:35.168
Just kidding, I have no idea
what any of this means.

05:35.168 --> 05:37.170
I want you
to forget everything you know

05:37.170 --> 05:38.505
about water and glycol-based
cooling.

05:38.505 --> 05:40.256
- Done.
- I'm ready to make an offer.

05:40.256 --> 05:41.216
I haven't started
the pitch yet.

05:41.216 --> 05:42.801
Don't sell past the "yes."

05:42.801 --> 05:44.552
The typical design consists
of primary

05:44.552 --> 05:47.764
and secondary coil windings,
but the operative word--

05:47.764 --> 05:49.307
- Design.
- Coil.

05:49.307 --> 05:52.018
With silicon anodes, we see
higher lithium absorption,

05:52.018 --> 05:54.354
as silicon can bind
four lithium ions

05:54.354 --> 05:56.523
- per silicon atom.
- This is game-changing.

05:56.523 --> 05:58.191
- It's a game changer.
- The game has changed.

05:58.191 --> 06:00.068
This'll change the game.

06:00.068 --> 06:02.278
[sighs] I cannot take
much more of this.

06:02.278 --> 06:03.947
So many different types
of nerd,

06:03.947 --> 06:06.282
each with their own
distinct odor.

06:06.282 --> 06:08.159
Well,
our next meeting cancelled.

06:08.159 --> 06:10.245
The company dissolved and laid
off its entire workforce.

06:10.245 --> 06:12.163
- Oh, thank God.
- Oh, that's perfect.

06:12.163 --> 06:13.790
We can meet Chase.
His company is right around

06:13.790 --> 06:15.041
- here.
- Or we could go to

06:15.041 --> 06:16.001
that boba shop that we passed
on the way here.

06:16.001 --> 06:17.127
Oh, I vote for that.

06:17.127 --> 06:18.628
I love me some boba.

06:18.628 --> 06:20.797
- It's so good.
- It's nice to chew a drink.

06:20.797 --> 06:22.465
Guys, come on.
We're meeting with every

06:22.465 --> 06:23.883
company Cyrus wanted to.

06:23.883 --> 06:26.761
- I'm just asking for one.
- Oh, baby brother is jealous.

06:26.761 --> 06:27.971
[whiny] Does baby need a toy?

06:27.971 --> 06:29.931
- [cooing]
- Fine! Forget it.

06:29.931 --> 06:31.307
Uh, message received, okay?

06:31.307 --> 06:33.393
I'm dumb,
and everything I say is stupid.

06:33.393 --> 06:34.519
- Mm-hmm.
- [sighs]

06:34.519 --> 06:36.730
Okay, Wesley,
we'll meet your friend.

06:36.730 --> 06:38.273
- Seriously?
- Yeah.

06:38.273 --> 06:39.858
Yes!
You will not regret this.

06:39.858 --> 06:41.484
I personally vouch
for this guy.

06:41.484 --> 06:42.694
Mm.

06:42.694 --> 06:45.739
<i>[light music]</i>

06:45.739 --> 06:48.158
Wesley Payne in the house!

06:48.158 --> 06:51.161
- Oh, there he is.
- Sarah, pump up the AC

06:51.161 --> 06:53.830
because this guy comes in hot.

06:53.830 --> 06:55.623
Uh.
[both laugh]

06:55.623 --> 06:57.167
- My man.
- Yeah.

06:57.167 --> 06:59.502
What in white-boy hell
is this?

06:59.502 --> 07:01.838
Uh, Chase Brody,
this is Katherine Hastings--

07:01.838 --> 07:03.298
Katherine the Great,
I call her.

07:03.298 --> 07:05.800
That's Sexy Sadie,
Jack the Knife,

07:05.800 --> 07:09.429
and Cyrus, um, uh,
the Glasses Guy.

07:09.429 --> 07:11.431
Well, thanks
for comin' out here, fam.

07:11.431 --> 07:13.058
Yeah, well,
our last pitch cancelled,

07:13.058 --> 07:14.225
so we have a very short window

07:14.225 --> 07:16.061
for a quick, quick meet
and greet.

07:16.061 --> 07:17.520
- Mm-hmm.
- So how do you two

07:17.520 --> 07:19.564
- know each other? [laughs]
- Wesley and I go way back.

07:19.564 --> 07:22.025
I used to cheat off him
in college.

07:22.025 --> 07:23.818
[laughs] Right.

07:23.818 --> 07:25.570
[inhales deeply]

07:25.570 --> 07:26.529
Oh, you're serious.

07:26.529 --> 07:29.074
Yeah, no.
He's got some strengths.

07:29.074 --> 07:30.283
All right, well,
if you guys wanna follow me,

07:30.283 --> 07:32.035
- I can give you the grand tour.
- Oh, great.

07:32.035 --> 07:34.537
We'd love a real quick,
short tour.

07:34.537 --> 07:37.248
Mm, so he's less intelligent
than Wesley.

07:37.248 --> 07:38.708
- God help us.
- Yeah.

07:38.708 --> 07:41.461
Take a seat.
Make yourselves comfortable.

07:41.461 --> 07:46.216
This is
our chief "sand-gineer,"

07:46.216 --> 07:47.926
Dustin Kregg.
He's like the Woz

07:47.926 --> 07:50.095
to my Jobs.
He does the science.

07:50.095 --> 07:51.888
I do the vision.

07:51.888 --> 07:56.726
Hi...

07:56.726 --> 08:00.063
I, uh, like your tie.

08:00.063 --> 08:01.606
I like yours too.

08:01.606 --> 08:04.567
<i>[soft reflective music]</i>

08:04.567 --> 08:06.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:06.486 --> 08:07.779
What is sand?

08:07.779 --> 08:09.489
Tiny rocks?

08:09.489 --> 08:13.118
That stuff we play in
at the beach?

08:13.118 --> 08:15.412
Well,
what if the actual particles

08:15.412 --> 08:19.165
that we drive by
when we drive by the beach

08:19.165 --> 08:22.961
could actually be powering
what we drive

08:22.961 --> 08:25.755
when we drive by the beach?

08:25.755 --> 08:27.716
- What is he talking about?
- I didn't get any of that.

08:27.716 --> 08:30.844
We've learned how to harness
the power of the sun,

08:30.844 --> 08:32.220
the wind, and water.

08:32.220 --> 08:34.264
Why not the power of sand?

08:34.264 --> 08:37.225
Wait, he's not actually
pitching a battery made

08:37.225 --> 08:38.393
- of sand, right?
- I give you...

08:38.393 --> 08:40.603
- No, he can't be.
- The world's first

08:40.603 --> 08:44.357
sand-based battery,
the sandtery.

08:44.357 --> 08:46.151
- Oh, my God. I think he is.
- For generations--

08:46.151 --> 08:49.154
- Should we leave?
- Are you kidding?

08:49.154 --> 08:50.864
I don't wanna miss a second
of this.

08:50.864 --> 08:52.240
- Guys, shh!
- Isn't it time

08:52.240 --> 08:54.284
we built on something new?

08:54.284 --> 08:55.410
Oh, please say
"built on sand."

08:55.410 --> 08:56.536
Oh, God, that would make me
so happy.

08:56.536 --> 08:57.620
Isn't it time

08:57.620 --> 09:00.373
we built... on sand?

09:00.373 --> 09:02.292
- [both laugh]
- Revolutionizing the world--

09:02.292 --> 09:04.085
Shh. You're being rude.

09:04.085 --> 09:05.462
- Everything okay?
- Oh, oh, yeah.

09:05.462 --> 09:07.630
Everything is more than okay, yeah.

09:07.630 --> 09:09.632
No, this is fantastic.
Please keep going.

09:09.632 --> 09:11.134
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

09:11.134 --> 09:14.095
So here in our lab,
our scientists work

09:14.095 --> 09:16.139
to manipulate the chemistry
of sand

09:16.139 --> 09:18.516
to hold and transfer electricity

09:18.516 --> 09:20.477
using the principles
of physics.

09:20.477 --> 09:22.520
Wow,
that sounds very sciencey.

09:22.520 --> 09:24.856
Yes, I think that physics
is actually the most sciencey

09:24.856 --> 09:26.149
of all the sciences. [laughs]

09:26.149 --> 09:27.525
You guys are being
so annoying right now.

09:27.525 --> 09:29.652
And so over here is
sort of the sand area.

09:29.652 --> 09:31.738
There's thousands
of different types of sand.

09:31.738 --> 09:33.031
It can be finicky.

09:33.031 --> 09:34.783
I was trying to ask
about their financials.

09:34.783 --> 09:37.869
I'm not totally clear
on their business model.

09:37.869 --> 09:39.829
Oh, it's--it's really simple.

09:39.829 --> 09:41.164
We give them money.

09:41.164 --> 09:43.333
They put it in
a Cayman Island bank account.

09:43.333 --> 09:45.752
- We never hear from them again.
- [laughs]

09:45.752 --> 09:47.337
Yeah, they didn't teach us
that one in class yet.

09:47.337 --> 09:48.546
- Mm.
- [laughs]

09:50.215 --> 09:51.591
Hey, will you stick close by?

09:51.591 --> 09:53.968
That creepy guy keeps
on staring at me.

09:53.968 --> 09:56.888
Which creepy guy?

09:56.888 --> 09:58.890
Uh, Jack,

09:58.890 --> 10:00.767
the one with the notebook.

10:00.767 --> 10:03.687
He weirds me out. [laughs]

10:03.687 --> 10:05.980
Don't worry.

10:05.980 --> 10:08.191
I won't let him near you.

10:08.191 --> 10:10.527
- Thanks.
- All right, everybody.

10:10.527 --> 10:14.572
I'd like to introduce
to you the future of energy,

10:14.572 --> 10:15.824
the sandtery.

10:15.824 --> 10:16.950
[clicks]

10:16.950 --> 10:18.159
- Oh.
- Oh, wow.

10:18.159 --> 10:19.369
- Wow, it works.
- [laughs]

10:19.369 --> 10:20.912
